ExplntnTxt: Rensselaer is a school described in Section 170(b)(1(A)(ii) and checked box 2 on Schedul A, Part I on the current year and previously filed Form 990 returns. Instructions for Form 990, Part IV, line 2 requires an organization to answer "Yes" if it meets the 33 1/3% support test of the requlations under sections 509(a)(1) and 170(b)(1)(A)(vi), checks the box on Schedule A, Part II, line 13, 16a or 16b and received from any one contributor contributions of the greater of $5,000 or 2% of the amount on Part VIII, line 1h. Rensselaer meets this test and have answered "Yes" to Part IV, line 2 which requires completing Schedule B. Furthermore, the instructions states that an organization filing Schedule B can limit the contributors it reports on Schedule B to greater than 2% of the amount on Part VIII, line 1h only if it checks the box on Schedule A, Part II, line 13, 16a or 16b. However, the tax software that Rensslaer uses to prepare the Form 990 will not display Schedule A, Part II when box 2 is checked on Schedule A, Part I. To be compliant with the instructions for Form 990, Part IV, line 2, Rensselaer is submitting the completed Scheduel A, Part II as a separate attachment.

FrmAndLnRfrncDsc: Part I: Additional Information
ExplntnTxt: Rensselaer is a school described in Section 170(b)(1(A)(ii) and checked box 2 on Schedul A, Part I on the current year and previously filed Form 990 returns. Instructions for Form 990, Part IV, line 2 requires an organization to answer "Yes" if it meets the 33 1/3% support test of the requlations under sections 509(a)(1) and 170(b)(1)(A)(vi), checks the box on Schedule A, Part II, line 13, 16a or 16b and received from any one contributor contributions of the greater of $5,000 or 2% of the amount on Part VIII, line 1h. Rensselaer meets this test and have answered "Yes" to Part IV, line 2 which requires completing Schedule B. Furthermore, the instructions states that an organization filing Schedule B can limit the contributors it reports on Schedule B to greater than 2% of the amount on Part VIII, line 1h only if it checks the box on Schedule A, Part II, line 13, 16a or 16b. However, the tax software that Rensslaer uses to prepare the Form 990 will not display Schedule A, Part II when box 2 is checked on Schedule A, Part I. To be compliant with the instructions for Form 990, Part IV, line 2, Rensselaer is submitting the completed Scheduel A, Part II as a separate attachment.

PER THE 2013 INSTRUCTIONS FOR SCHEDULE B, SCHEDULE OF CONTRIBUTORS, THE INTERNAL REVENUE SERVICE HAS CLARIFIED THAT IN ORDER FOR THE UNIVERSITY TO REPORT ITS CONTRIBUTIONS UNDER THE SPECIAL RULE, THE ORGANIZATION MUST NOW CHECK BOX 7 OF SCHEDULE A, PART I, AND COMPLETE SCHEDULE A, PART II, SUPPORT SCHEDULE FOR ORGANIZATIONS DESCRIBED IN SECTIONS 170(B)(1)(A)(IV) AND 170(B)(1)(A)(VI).

FrmAndLnRfrncDsc: PART IV, SECTION D, LINE 3:
ExplntnTxt: THE LSU SCHOOL OF MEDICINE IN NEW ORLEANS FACULTY GROUP PRACTICE (LSUHN) IS A SUPPORTING ORGANIZATION OF LSU HEALTH SCIENCES CENTER - NEW ORLEANS (LSUHSC). ITS PURPOSE IS TO PROVIDE MEDICAL, EDUCATIONAL, AND RESEARCH FUNCTIONS FOR LSUHSC. IF IT DID NOT ENGAGE IN THESE ACTIVITIES, LSUHSC WOULD HAVE TO PROVIDE THEM ITSELF. LSUHN'S FINANCE AND EXECUTIVE COMMITTEES ARE CONTROLLED BY LSUHSC AND THIS ENABLES LSUHSC TO HAVE A SIGNIFICANT VOICE IN THE OPERATIONS OF LSUHN. AS SUCH, THESE COMMITTEES CONTROL THE USE OF THE INCOME AND ASSETS OF LSUHN AND PAYMENTS MADE TO LSUHSC. IN ADDITION, THE FINANCE COMMITTEE SETS THE INVESTMENT POLICIES OF LSUHN. LSUHN IS CONSIDERED A BLENDED COMPONENT UNIT OF THE UNIVERSITY SYSTEM AND IS INCLUDED IN THE LOUISIANA STATE UNIVERSITY SYSTEM FINANCIAL STATEMENTS. THE COMPONENT UNIT IS INCLUDED IN THE REPORTING ENTITY BECAUSE OF THE SIGNIFICANCE OF ITS OPERATIONAL AND FINANCIAL RELATIONSHIPS WITH THE LSU SYSTEM AND THE LSUHSC. THIS BLENDING PROVIDES THE LSU SYSTEM AND LSUHSC WITH FULL KNOWLEDGE OF THE FINANCIAL MATTERS OF LSUHN.

ExplntnTxt: The Faculty Club at the University of California San Diego (UCSD) is physically located on the UCSD campus with long term lease from the University. The club was founded in 1988 to provide a place in a central location for colleagues and community to socialize and intellectualize over food in a casual atmosphere of UCSD. Membership in the club is required for participation and is limited to faculty, staff and graduate students as well and retired employees, community members with an interest in the educational and intellectual life of the campus, persons at other select non-profit research institutions, Chancellors Associates and select businesses adding to the educational and intellectual life of the campus (must be approved by 2/3 vote of the board), and campus departments. Luncheon meals are served weekdays and periodic special events scheduled.

FrmAndLnRfrncDsc: Part IV, Section E, Line 2b:
ExplntnTxt: Without the Faculty Club no single space of sufficient size would be available regularly nor meals served. The casual atmosphere and central location of the club serves as a focal point for university employees and supporters. It allows formal and informal gatherings of university colleagues and a meeting place for activities. Some of these activities would continue on an ad hoc basis in the absence of the club but the club was established to facilitate these interactions.

FrmAndLnRfrncDsc: PART IV, SECTION E, LINE 2A
ExplntnTxt: THE SUPPORTED ORGANIZATION IS KANSAS STATE UNIVERSITY (KSU). FrmAndLnRfrncDsc: PART IV, SECTION E, LINE 2B
ExplntnTxt: TECHNOLOGY TRANSFER IS CLOSELY LINKED TO FUNDAMENTAL RESEARCH ACTIVITIES IN UNIVERSITIES. WITH THIS ELECTION, UNIVERSITIES ARE REQUIRED TO PROPERLY MANAGE THE INVENTIONS INCLUDING REPORTING REQUIREMENTS, FILING PATENTS, MARKETING AND LICENSING THE INVENTION AND DISTRIBUTING RETURNS. THE REQUIREMENTS NECESSARY TO ADHERE TO THE BAYH-DOLE ACT ARE CONTRACTED TO KANSAS STATE UNIVERSITY RESEARCH FOUNDATION BY KSU. IF THE KANSAS STATE UNIVERSITY RESEARCH FOUNDATION DID NOT EXIST, KSU WOULD STILL BE REQUIRED TO CONFORM TO THESE REQUIREMENTS.

FrmAndLnRfrncDsc: Schedule A, Part II, Line 17a 10% FACTS & CIRCUMSTANCES TEST 2015
ExplntnTxt: TREAS. REGS. SECTION 1.170A-9(F)(3)(I) PROVIDES THAT IN ORDER TO MEET THE "FACTS AND CIRCUMSTANCES" TEST, THE ORGANIZATION MUST NORMALLY RECEIVE SUBSTANTIAL SUPPORT (MORE THAN 10%) FROM CONTRIBUTIONS FROM GOVERNMENTAL UNITS, THE GENERAL PUBLIC, OR A COMBINATION OF THESE SOURCES. COMPLETE COLLEGE HAS RECEIVED APPROXIMATELY 21.98% IN PUBLIC SUPPORT, SUBSTANTIALLY ABOVE THE 10% THRESHOLD. IN ADDITION TO THE 10% THRESHOLD TEST, TREAS. REGS. SECTION 1.170A-9(F)(3)(II) PROVIDES THAT THE ORGANIZATION MUST BE ORGANIZED AND OPERATED SO AS TO ATTRACT NEW AND ADDITIONAL PUBLIC OR GOVERNMENTAL SUPPORT ON A CONTINUOUS BASIS. AN ORGANIZATION WILL MEET THIS REQUIREMENT IF IT: - MAINTAINS A CONTINUOUS AND BONA FIDE PROGRAM FOR THE SOLICITATION OF FUNDS FROM THE GENERAL PUBLIC, OR -IT CARRIES ON ACTIVITIES DESIGNED TO ATTRACT SUPPORT FROM THE GOVERNMENT OR 509(A)(1) CHARITIES. COMPLETE COLLEGE SATISFIES BOTH TESTS. IT MAINTAINS A CONTINUOUS AND BONA FIDE PROGRAM FOR CHARITABLE CONTRIBUTIONS FROM THE PUBLIC AND CARRIES ON THE TYPE OF CHARITABLE ACTIVITIES THAT ARE DESIGNED TO ATTRACT SUPPORT FROM GOVERNMENTAL UNITS AND THE GENERAL PUBLIC AS IS EVIDENCED BY THE SIGNIFICANT STATE GOVERNMENT INVOLVEMENT WITH COMPLETE COLLEGE IN ITS "COMPLETION PROGRAM".

Part I: Additional Information
ExplntnTxt: Rensselaer is a school described in Section 170(b)(1(A)(ii) and checked box 2 on Schedul A, Part I on the current year and previously filed Form 990 returns. Instructions for Form 990, Part IV, line 2 requires an organization to answer "Yes" if it meets the 33 1/3% support test of the requlations under sections 509(a)(1) and 170(b)(1)(A)(vi), checks the box on Schedule A, Part II, line 13, 16a or 16b and received from any one contributor contributions of the greater of $5,000 or 2% of the amount on Part VIII, line 1h. Rensselaer meets this test and have answered "Yes" to Part IV, line 2 which requires completing Schedule B. Furthermore, the instructions states that an organization filing Schedule B can limit the contributors it reports on Schedule B to greater than 2% of the amount on Part VIII, line 1h only if it checks the box on Schedule A, Part II, line 13, 16a or 16b. However, the tax software that Rensslaer uses to prepare the Form 990 will not display Schedule A, Part II when box 2 is checked on Schedule A, Part I. To be compliant with the instructions for Form 990, Part IV, line 2, Rensselaer is submitting the completed Scheduel A, Part II as a separate attachment.

ExplntnTxt: ON APRIL 21, 2016, JOHNSON UNIVERSITY RECEIVED A LETTER FROM THE INTERNAL REVENUE SERVICE (IRS) STATING THEY HAD CONSIDERED THE UNIVERSITY'S APPLICATION FOR A GROUP EXEMPTION LETTER RECOGNIZING ITS SUBORDINATES AS EXEMPT FROM FEDERAL INCOME TAX UNDER SECTION 501(A) OF THE INTERNAL REVENUE CODE AS ORGANIZATIONS OF THE TYPE DESCRIBED IN SECTION 501(C)(3). ADDITIONALLY, THE IRS CLASSIFIED THE ORGANIZATIONS THAT JOHNSON UNIVERSITY OPERATES, SUPERVISES, OR CONTROLS, AND THAT ARE COVERED BY THE UNIVERSITY'S NOTIFICATION TO THE IRS, AS ORGANIZATIONS THAT ARE NOT PRIVATE FOUNDATIONS BECAUSE THEY ARE ORGANIZATIONS OF THE TYPE DESCRIBED IN SECTIONS 509(A)(1) AND 170(B)(1)(A)(II) OF THE CODE. JOHNSON UNIVERSITY FLORIDA, INC., A GROUP SUBORDINATE ORGANIZATION OF JOHNSON UNIVERSITY, IS IDENTIFIED IN SCHEDULE A, PART I, LINE 2 AS A SCHOOL. IT IS AN EDUCATIONAL ORGANIZATION WHICH NORMALLY MAINTAINS A REGULAR FACULTY AND CURRICULUM AND NORMALLY HAS A REGULARLY ENROLLED BODY OF PUPILS OR STUDENTS IN ATTENDANCE AT THE PLACE WHERE ITS EDUCATIONAL ACTIVITIES ARE REGULARLY CARRIED ON. PER THE 2013 INSTRUCTIONS FOR SCHEDULE B, SCHEDULE OF CONTRIBUTORS, THE INTERNAL REVENUE SERVICE HAS CLARIFIED THAT IN ORDER FOR THE UNIVERSITY TO REPORT ITS CONTRIBUTIONS UNDER THE SPECIAL RULE, THE ORGANIZATION MUST NOW CHECK BOX 7 OF SCHEDULE A, PART I, AND COMPLETE SCHEDULE A, PART II, SUPPORT SCHEDULE FOR ORGANIZATIONS DESCRIBED IN SECTIONS 170(B)(1)(A)(IV) AND 170(B)(1)(A)(VI).

FrmAndLnRfrncDsc: Part I: Additional Information
ExplntnTxt: Rensselaer is a school described in Section 170(b)(1(A)(ii) and checked box 2 on Schedul A, Part I on the current year and previously filed Form 990 returns. Instructions for Form 990, Part IV, line 2 requires an organization to answer "Yes" if it meets the 33 1/3% support test of the requlations under sections 509(a)(1) and 170(b)(1)(A)(vi), checks the box on Schedule A, Part II, line 13, 16a or 16b and received from any one contributor contributions of the greater of $5,000 or 2% of the amount on Part VIII, line 1h. Rensselaer meets this test and have answered "Yes" to Part IV, line 2 which requires completing Schedule B. Furthermore, the instructions states that an organization filing Schedule B can limit the contributors it reports on Schedule B to greater than 2% of the amount on Part VIII, line 1h only if it checks the box on Schedule A, Part II, line 13, 16a or 16b. However, the tax software that Rensslaer uses to prepare the Form 990 will not display Schedule A, Part II when box 2 is checked on Schedule A, Part I. To be compliant with the instructions for Form 990, Part IV, line 2, Rensselaer is submitting the completed Scheduel A, Part II as a separate attachment.

ExplntnTxt: JOHNSON BIBLE COLLEGE RECEIVED AN IRS DETERMINATION LETTER IN DECEMBER, 1942 STATING THAT THE ORGANIZATION WAS RECOGNIZED AS AN ORGANIZATION EXEMPT FROM FEDERAL INCOME TAX UNDER SECTION 501(C)(3) OF THE INTERNAL REVENUE CODE. ADDITIONALLY, THE ORGANIZATION WAS ALSO DETERMINED NOT TO BE A PRIVATE FOUNDATION AS DEFINED IN SECTION 509(A) OF THE CODE BECAUSE IT WAS AN ORGANIZATION DESCRIBED IN SECTION 509(A)(1) AND SECTION 170(B)(1)(A)(II), WHICH IS IDENTIFIED IN SCHEDULE A, PART I, LINE 2 AS A SCHOOL. IT IS AN EDUCATIONAL ORGANIZATION WHICH NORMALLY MAINTAINS A REGULAR FACULTY AND CURRICULUM AND NORMALLY HAS A REGULARLY ENROLLED BODY OF PUPILS OR STUDENTS IN ATTENDANCE AT THE PLACE WHERE ITS EDUCATIONAL ACTIVITIES ARE REGULARLY CARRIED ON. ON JULY 1, 2011, JOHNSON BIBLE COLLEGE CHANGED ITS NAME TO JOHNSON UNIVERSITY. PER THE 2013 INSTRUCTIONS FOR SCHEDULE B, SCHEDULE OF CONTRIBUTORS, THE INTERNAL REVENUE SERVICE HAS CLARIFIED THAT IN ORDER FOR THE UNIVERSITY TO REPORT ITS CONTRIBUTIONS UNDER THE SPECIAL RULE, THE ORGANIZATION MUST NOW CHECK BOX 7 OF SCHEDULE A, PART I, AND COMPLETE SCHEDULE A, PART II, SUPPORT SCHEDULE FOR ORGANIZATIONS DESCRIBED IN SECTIONS 170(B)(1)(A)(IV) AND 170(B)(1)(A)(VI).

FrmAndLnRfrncDsc: PART IV, SECTION D, LINE 3:
ExplntnTxt: THE LSU SCHOOL OF MEDICINE IN NEW ORLEANS FACULTY GROUP PRACTICE (LSUHN) IS A SUPPORTING ORGANIZATION OF LSU HEALTH SCIENCES CENTER - NEW ORLEANS (LSUHSC). ITS PURPOSE IS TO PROVIDE MEDICAL, EDUCATIONAL, AND RESEARCH FUNCTIONS FOR LSUHSC. IF IT DID NOT ENGAGE IN THESE ACTIVITIES, LSUHSC WOULD HAVE TO PROVIDE THEM ITSELF. LSUHN'S FINANCE AND EXECUTIVE COMMITTEES ARE CONTROLLED BY LSUHSC AND THIS ENABLES LSUHSC TO HAVE A SIGNIFICANT VOICE IN THE OPERATIONS OF LSUHN. AS SUCH, THESE COMMITTEES CONTROL THE USE OF THE INCOME AND ASSETS OF LSUHN AND PAYMENTS MADE TO LSUHSC. IN ADDITION, THE FINANCE COMMITTEE SETS THE INVESTMENT POLICIES OF LSUHN. ExplntnTxt: The Faculty Club at the University of California San Diego (UCSD) is physically located on the UCSD campus with long term lease from the University. The club was founded in 1988 to provide a place in a central location for colleagues and community to socialize and intellectualize over food in a casual atmosphere of UCSD. Membership in the club is required for participation and is limited to faculty, staff and graduate students as well and retired employees, community members with an interest in the educational and intellectual life of the campus, persons at other select non-profit research institutions, Chancellors Associates and select businesses adding to the educational and intellectual life of the campus (must be approved by 2/3 vote of the board), and campus departments. Luncheon meals are served weekdays and periodic special events scheduled.

FrmAndLnRfrncDsc: Part IV, Section E, Line 2b:
ExplntnTxt: Without the Faculty Club no single space of sufficient size would be available regularly nor meals served. The casual atmosphere and central location of the club serves as a focal point for university employees and supporters. It allows formal and informal gatherings of university colleagues and a meeting place for activities. Some of these activities would continue on an ad hoc basis in the absence of the club but the club was established to facilitate these interactions.

FrmAndLnRfrncDsc: PART IV, SECTION E, LINE 2A
ExplntnTxt: THE SUPPORTED ORGANIZATION IS KANSAS STATE UNIVERSITY (KSU). KANSAS STATE UNIVERSITY RESEARCH FOUNDATION (KSURF) IS RESPONSIBLE FOR MANAGING THE TECHNOLOGY TRANSFER ACTIVITIES OF KSU UNDER AN OPERATING AGREEMENT BETWEEN THE TWO ENTITIES. KSURF WAS ESTABLISHED TO PROMOTE, ENCOURAGE AND AID SCIENTIFIC RESEARCH AT KSU AND TO PROVIDE THE MEANS, METHODS AND AGENCIES BY WHICH INVENTIONS AND DISCOVERIES AT KSU MAY BE PATENTED, COMMERCIALIZED OR OTHERWISE UTILIZED FOR THE BENEFIT OF KSU AND ITS FACULTY, STAFF, ALUMNI AND STUDENTS.

FrmAndLnRfrncDsc: PART IV, SECTION E, LINE 2B
ExplntnTxt: TECHNOLOGY TRANSFER IS CLOSELY LINKED TO FUNDAMENTAL RESEARCH ACTIVITIES IN UNIVERSITIES. UNDER THE BAYH-DOLE ACT OF 1980, UNIVERSITIES HAVE THE ABILITY TO RETAIN TITLE TO AND PROMOTE THE COMMERCIALIZATION OF INVENTIONS DEVELOPED UNDER GOVERNMENT FUNDING. WITH THIS ELECTION, UNIVERSITIES ARE REQUIRED TO PROPERLY MANAGE THE INVENTIONS INCLUDING REPORTING REQUIREMENTS, FILING PATENTS, MARKETING AND LICENSING THE INVENTION AND DISTRIBUTING RETURNS. THE REQUIREMENTS NECESSARY TO ADHERE TO THE BAYH-DOLE ACT ARE CONTRACTED TO KANSAS STATE UNIVERSITY RESEARCH FOUNDATION BY KSU. IF THE KANSAS STATE UNIVERSITY RESEARCH FOUNDATION DID NOT EXIST, KSU WOULD STILL BE REQUIRED TO CONFORM TO THESE REQUIREMENTS.

SECTION 1.170A-9(F)(3)(II) PROVIDES THAT THE ORGANIZATION MUST BE ORGANIZED AND OPERATED SO AS TO ATTRACT NEW AND ADDITIONAL PUBLIC OR GOVERNMENTAL SUPPORT ON A CONTINUOUS BASIS. AN ORGANIZATION WILL MEET THIS REQUIREMENT IF IT: - MAINTAINS A CONTINUOUS AND BONA FIDE PROGRAM FOR THE SOLICITATION OF FUNDS FROM THE GENERAL PUBLIC, OR -IT CARRIES ON ACTIVITIES DESIGNED TO ATTRACT SUPPORT FROM THE GOVERNMENT OR 509(A)(1) CHARITIES. COMPLETE COLLEGE SATISFIES BOTH TESTS. IT MAINTAINS A CONTINUOUS AND BONA FIDE PROGRAM FOR CHARITABLE CONTRIBUTIONS FROM THE PUBLIC AND CARRIES ON THE TYPE OF CHARITABLE ACTIVITIES THAT ARE DESIGNED TO ATTRACT SUPPORT FROM GOVERNMENTAL UNITS AND THE GENERAL PUBLIC AS IS EVIDENCED BY THE SIGNIFICANT STATE GOVERNMENT INVOLVEMENT WITH COMPLETE COLLEGE IN ITS "COMPLETION PROGRAM".
